# .windsurfrules — TavernKeep Development Guidelines

These rules govern all AI-assisted code generation in this project. Follow them precisely on every file creation, edit, or refactor.

---

## 1. Project Identity

- **App name**: TavernKeep
- **Purpose**: D&D shop management and sharing platform for DMs and players
- **Stack**: Next.js 14 (App Router) · TypeScript · Tailwind CSS · shadcn/ui · Supabase · Google Gemini API · Google Stitch (design) · Vercel

---

## 2. Git Workflow (Windows/PowerShell)

**NEVER use `&&` to chain commands.** PowerShell does not support it — use `;` or separate commands.

```powershell
# ❌ BAD — PowerShell parse error
git add -A && git commit -m "message"

# ✅ GOOD — semicolon for sequential execution
git add -A; git commit -m "message"
```

**If `.git/index.lock` persists:** run `Remove-Item .git\index.lock`.

### Commit Message Format
```
feat: add AI shopkeeper generation endpoint
fix: strip hidden items from player shop API
chore: add RLS policy for party_access table
ui: implement player shop view from Stitch design
db: migration for inventory volatility fields
design: update DESIGN.md from Stitch token extraction
```

---

## 3. Google Stitch Design Workflow (ALWAYS DO THIS FIRST)

Before writing any UI code for a screen or component:

1. Use the Stitch MCP to list available projects and screens
2. Fetch the Design DNA for the relevant screen (fonts, colors, spacing, layout)
3. Retrieve the screen's HTML as a pixel-perfect reference
4. If this is the first screen built, generate a `DESIGN.md` in the project root containing all extracted design tokens
5. Implement the component in React + Tailwind, matching the Stitch design exactly

**If no Stitch screen exists**, use tokens already in `DESIGN.md`. Never invent new colors, fonts, or spacing.

`DESIGN.md` is auto-generated from Stitch — never hand-edit it. It is the single source of truth for the design system.

---

## 4. TypeScript Rules

- **Strict mode always on.** No `any`. No `@ts-ignore` unless absolutely unavoidable and documented.
- All props interfaces named `[ComponentName]Props`
- All DB row types live in `/types/database.ts` as exported interfaces
- All API request/response bodies validated with `zod` schemas in `/lib/validators/`
- Use `type` for unions/intersections; use `interface` for object shapes

---

## 5. File and Folder Structure

```
/app/(auth)/          → Auth pages
/app/(dm)/            → DM-protected pages
/app/(player)/        → Public player pages
/app/api/             → API route handlers
/components/ui/       → shadcn/ui primitives (never modify directly)
/components/dm/       → DM-specific components
/components/player/   → Player-specific components
/components/shared/   → Shared components
/lib/supabase/        → Supabase client helpers (server.ts, client.ts, middleware.ts)
/lib/prompts/         → All AI prompt strings as named exports
/lib/validators/      → Zod schemas
/lib/utils/           → Pure utility functions
/lib/constants/       → App-wide constants
/types/database.ts    → DB row interfaces
/types/index.ts       → Re-exports
/hooks/               → Custom React hooks
/supabase/migrations/ → All schema migrations
DESIGN.md             → Stitch-extracted design tokens (auto-generated, do not hand-edit)
```

- One component per file
- File names: `kebab-case.tsx` for components, `camelCase.ts` for utilities

---

## 6. Component Rules

- **Server Components by default.** Add `"use client"` only when the component needs hooks, event handlers, browser APIs, or Zustand.
- Never fetch data in Client Components — pass it as props from Server Components
- All interactive forms are Client Components using `react-hook-form` + `zod`
- No inline styles. Tailwind utility classes only. Use CSS variables from `DESIGN.md`.
- All images use Next.js `<Image />` with explicit `width`, `height`, and `alt`
- No `<a>` tags for internal navigation — use Next.js `<Link />`

---

## 7. Testing Rules

**Every feature must have tests. No exceptions.**

### Test-First Development
1. Write tests BEFORE or WITH the feature — never after
2. Run `npm test` before every commit — all tests must pass
3. Run `npm run build` before pushing — build must succeed
4. Never push broken tests to GitHub

### What Requires Tests
| Feature Type | Test Type | Location |
|---|---|---|
| New component | Unit test (`@testing-library/react`) | `__tests__/components/` |
| API route | Unit test with mocked deps | `__tests__/api/` |
| Server action | Unit test with mocked Supabase | `__tests__/actions/` |
| Database logic | Integration / RLS policy test | `__tests__/security/` |
| Utility function | Unit test with edge cases | `__tests__/utils/` |
| Complex flow | E2E with Playwright | `e2e/` |

### Standards
- **Jest is the sole testing framework** — no Vitest, no Mocha
- All tests in `__tests__/**/*.test.{ts,tsx}`; E2E in `e2e/` (excluded from Jest)
- Mock all external dependencies (Supabase, AI clients, fetch)
- Test behavior, not implementation. Include error cases.
- Use `describe` blocks for logical grouping
- Security tests must verify RLS prevents unauthorized access

### Test Scripts
```bash
npm test                  # All tests
npm run test:watch        # Watch mode
npm run test:security     # Security/RLS only
npm run test:admin        # Admin tests
```

